# ipmi Provider

Manage BMC/iDRAC hardware via IPMI 2.0 (LAN+) by wrapping the `ipmitool`
CLI. Resources can override any of the provider-block connection fields
per-host for multi-BMC fleets.

> **Canonical Registry source:** `markddavidoff/ipmitool`. Beware
> typo-squat namespaces — if your `source =` line is anything else,
> it's not this provider.

## Managing BMC credentials

`password = var.bmc_password` in a `.tfvars` file is the obvious
starting point — and the wrong long-term default. BMC credentials end
up in Terraform state and any backend that holds it. Source them
through one of the standard secret-store integrations instead.

### Pattern 1: SOPS-encrypted env file

Matches the pattern the provider's own acceptance tests use
(`secrets/idrac.enc.env` in the repo).

```hcl
terraform {
  required_providers {
    sops = { source = "carlpett/sops" }
    ipmi = { source = "markddavidoff/ipmitool" }
  }
}

data "sops_file" "bmc" {
  source_file = "${path.module}/bmc.enc.yaml"
}

provider "ipmi" {
  host         = "192.0.2.10"
  username     = data.sops_file.bmc.data["username"]
  password     = data.sops_file.bmc.data["password"]
  cipher_suite = 17
}
```

### Pattern 2: HashiCorp Vault

```hcl
data "vault_generic_secret" "bmc" {
  path = "kv/data/bmc/r210ii"
}

provider "ipmi" {
  host         = "192.0.2.10"
  username     = data.vault_generic_secret.bmc.data["username"]
  password     = data.vault_generic_secret.bmc.data["password"]
  cipher_suite = 17
}
```

### Pattern 3: Environment variable

For local development or simple CI setups, pass the password via
`TF_VAR_bmc_password` (the password still lands in state, but never
in a committed file):

```hcl
variable "bmc_password" {
  type      = string
  sensitive = true
}

provider "ipmi" {
  host         = "192.0.2.10"
  username     = "root"
  password     = var.bmc_password
  cipher_suite = 17
}
```

In all three patterns the resolved password is still serialized into
`terraform.tfstate`. The `ipmi_user.user_password_wo` field uses
WriteOnly so the BMC user-slot password it sets does NOT land in
state, but the *connection* password (used by every CRUD call) does.
Use an encrypted-at-rest state backend.

## Security & network requirements

IPMI is fundamentally a weak protocol. The provider's defaults are
secure where they can be, but several mitigations are network-level
and the adopter's responsibility.

### Network isolation

**IPMI must live on an isolated management VLAN, ACL'd to allow only
the Terraform runner IP(s) on UDP/623.** Do not expose BMCs to user or
internet networks. Several IPMI exploits assume reachability to UDP/623.

### Cipher suite

`cipher_suite = 17` (RAKP-HMAC-SHA256 + AES-128) is the right choice
wherever supported. `cipher_suite = 3` is RAKP-HMAC-SHA1 and only used
on legacy Dell 11G hardware. `cipher_suite = 0` disables RMCP+
authentication entirely and requires `allow_unauthenticated = true`
on the provider block as a guard against accidental use.

### CVE-2013-4786 (RAKP hash disclosure)

This is a **protocol-level** vulnerability that affects every RMCP+
implementation: an attacker who can reach UDP/623 can request the
RAKP message-2 hash for any username without authentication, then
offline-crack it. The provider can't fix this — only the network ACL
can.

Mitigation:
- BMC passwords ≥ 20 random characters, rotated quarterly.
- No direct access to UDP/623 from any user/internet network.
- Monitor for unusual ipmitool traffic on the mgmt VLAN.

### State backend

Treat read access to `terraform.tfstate` as equivalent to root on every
managed BMC. Use:
- S3 + SSE-KMS + restrictive IAM + CloudTrail data events, or
- Terraform Cloud / HCP Terraform with audit logging enabled, or
- An equivalent encrypted-at-rest backend.

Rotate BMC passwords on a schedule shorter than your state-file
retention.

### Audit logging

The provider emits structured `tflog` events for every BMC interaction:

- `WARN` — transient errors and retry attempts
- `INFO` — state-changing operations (power, user CRUD, LAN, channel,
  SOL, watchdog, boot device, chassis identify)
- `DEBUG` — every ipmitool invocation (visible at `TF_LOG=DEBUG`)

Every event includes `host`, `operation`, and (if configured) `run_id`.
Set `run_id` via the provider attribute or the `TF_IPMI_RUN_ID`
environment variable so SIEMs can join provider operations against
the CI runner's trigger log.

The provider can capture WHAT, WHEN, WHICH host, HOW (provider
version) — but not WHO (human attribution). Use runner-layer
correlation: GitHub Actions `github.actor`, Terraform Cloud principal,
Atlantis commenter, etc.

### Lockout-guard bypass

Three resources (`ipmi_user`, `ipmi_channel_access`, `ipmi_lan`)
include plan-time guards that block self-destructive applies. The
bypass is the `TF_IPMI_ALLOW_LOCKOUT=1` environment variable on the
runner — set only when you're intentionally renumbering or rotating
credentials.

### Upstream `ipmitool` CVEs

This provider invokes the system `ipmitool` binary. Keep it patched.
See https://github.com/ipmitool/ipmitool/security for upstream
vulnerability history.

## Quick start

```hcl
terraform {
  required_providers {
    ipmi = {
      source  = "markddavidoff/ipmitool"
      version = "~> 0.2"
    }
  }
}

provider "ipmi" {
  host         = "192.0.2.10"
  username     = "root"
  password     = var.bmc_password
  cipher_suite = 17    # see "Cipher suite" above
}

data "ipmi_chassis_status" "host" {}

resource "ipmi_power" "host" {
  state                = "on"
  power_off_on_destroy = false
}
```

